Bede knew what it was to suffer from want of books; speaking of Paterius' catena of passages from Gregory’s works explanatory of Holy Scripture, he says ε ‘quod opus si haberem ad. manuS, facilius mult-o . . studium meae uoluntatis imple- rem ; uerum . . . necdum illud merui uide1·e,’ix. 388. Hence he is anxious to popularise the knowledge which he has ac- quired: ‘ ut ad plurimos res ipsa perueniat: vi. 140. Another reason is the distance of himself and his readers from the pheno— mena described, ix. 200; a passage cited by S. D. i. 228, and given in the notes to H. E. v. 15 aclfin.
